Performs type conversion.

5=="5"

Output

true

Because

"5"

↓

5
===

Strict Equality

Checks

Value
Type
5==="5"

Output

false

Interview Shortcut

==

↓

Value only

===

↓

Value + Type
6. var vs let
var	let
Function Scope	Block Scope
Redeclare Allowed	Not Allowed
Hoisted	Hoisted but TDZ
Old JS	ES6

Example

if(true){

var a=10;

}

console.log(a);

Output

10

Now

if(true){

let a=10;

}

console.log(a);

Output

Reference Error

Why?

Because let is Block Scoped.

Interview Answer

var is function scoped while let is block scoped. let also prevents accidental redeclaration.

7. Type Coercion

Meaning

JavaScript automatically converts one data type into another.

Example

5+"5"

Output

55

Because

5

↓

"5"

↓

"55"

Another

5-"2"

Output

3

Because

"2"

↓

2

Interview Definition

Type coercion is JavaScript's automatic conversion of one data type into another.

8. Dynamic Typing

JavaScript variables have no fixed type.

Example

let x=10;

Later

x="Lucky";

Still valid.

Java

int x=10;

x="Lucky";

Compilation Error

Interview Answer

JavaScript is dynamically typed because variables can change types during runtime.

9. NaN

NaN means

Not a Number

Example

Number("Hello")

Output

NaN

Funny fact

typeof NaN

Output

number

Interview Answer

NaN represents an invalid numeric result.

10. Pass by Value vs Pass by Reference
Primitive

Passed by Value

let a=10;

let b=a;

a=20;

console.log(b);

Output

10
Object

Passed by Reference

let a={
name:"Lucky"
};

let b=a;

a.name="Raj";

console.log(b.name);

Output

Raj

Because both variables point to the same object.

Interview Answer

Primitive values are copied by value, while objects are shared by reference.

11. IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression)

Runs immediately after creation.

(function(){

console.log("Hello");

})();

Output

Hello

Used to avoid global variable pollution.

Interview Answer

IIFE is a function expression that executes immediately after it is defined.

12. Strict Mode
"use strict";

Makes JavaScript stricter.

Example

Without strict mode

x=10;

Works.

With strict mode

"use strict";

x=10;

Error

Because variable wasn't declared.

Interview Answer

Strict mode catches common JavaScript mistakes and prevents unsafe coding practices.

13. Higher Order Function

A function that

takes another function as argument
OR returns another function

Example

function greet(fn){

fn();

}

greet(function(){

console.log("Hi");

});

Examples in JavaScript

map()
filter()
reduce()
forEach()

Interview Answer

A higher-order function accepts another function as an argument or returns one.

14. this Keyword

Simple Rule:

this refers to the object that calls the function.

let person={

name:"Lucky",

show(){

console.log(this.name);

}

}

person.show();

Output

Lucky

Think

Object.Function()

↓

this = Object
